---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Contract-Driven Development — Eidos AGI"
  description="Contracts define what we want. Skills define how. Only one survives as AI improves."
>
    <article class="prose-page">
      <header class="page-hero">
        <h1>Contracts, Not Skills</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">The right primitive for AI systems.</p>
      </header>

      <section class="content-section">
        <p>The AI ecosystem is building skills — step-by-step instructions that tell models how to accomplish goals. Skills work today. They compensate for what the model can't figure out on its own.</p>
        <p>But skills are written based on today's weaknesses. Imagine writing a skills file for GPT-3 two years ago. It would be extremely verbose — every step spelled out, every edge case handled, every format detail specified. Today's models need less of that. Tomorrow's models need even less.</p>
        <p><strong>Skills are technical debt that accrues as models improve.</strong> Every step-by-step instruction is a bet that future models will be as limited as today's. That bet has never paid off.</p>
        <p>Contracts are the alternative. A contract defines what we want — the end state, the constraints, the guardrails. It does not define how to get there, what order to do things, or what tools to use. A contract says <em>what</em>. A skill says <em>how</em>. Models get better at <em>how</em> every six months. <em>What</em> doesn't change.</p>
        <p>Here are three real examples. Each shows the contract, what a model produces from it, and the skill it replaces.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- ── CONTRACT 1: Code Review ─────────────────────── -->
      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>Code review</h2>
        <p>The contract defines what "reviewed" means. The model decides how to review.</p>

        <div class="cdd-chart">
          <div class="cdd-chart-contract">
            <div class="cdd-chart-header">Contract</div>
            <pre><code>&#123;
  "file": "string — path to file",
  "findings": [&#123;
    "line": "integer",
    "severity": "critical | warning | suggestion",
    "issue": "string — what's wrong",
    "fix": "string — how to fix it"
  &#125;],
  "verdict": "approve | request-changes | block",
  "summary": "string — one sentence"
&#125;</code></pre>
          </div>
          <div class="cdd-chart-arrow">produces</div>
          <div class="cdd-chart-output">
            <div class="cdd-chart-header">Example output</div>
            <pre><code>&#123;
  "file": "src/auth/session.py",
  "findings": [
    &#123;
      "line": 42,
      "severity": "critical",
      "issue": "SQL injection — user input interpolated directly into query",
      "fix": "Use parameterized query: cursor.execute('SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = %s', (user_id,))"
    &#125;,
    &#123;
      "line": 87,
      "severity": "warning",
      "issue": "Bare except swallows KeyboardInterrupt",
      "fix": "Catch Exception, not BaseException"
    &#125;
  ],
  "verdict": "block",
  "summary": "SQL injection in auth path. Must fix before merge."
&#125;</code></pre>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="cdd-chart-skill">
          <div class="cdd-chart-header cdd-chart-header-skill">The skill this replaces <span class="cdd-fade">150 lines</span></div>
          <pre><code>Step 1: Read the file. Understand its role.
Step 2: Check for security issues (OWASP top 10, injection, XSS...)
Step 3: Check for performance (N+1, blocking calls, memory leaks...)
Step 4: Check error handling (bare except, swallowed errors...)
Step 5: Check logic (off-by-one, race conditions, null derefs...)
Step 6: Format as line-by-line findings with severity...
Step 7: Assign verdict: approve if 0 critical, request-changes if...
...eight more steps with edge cases and format rules...</code></pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── CONTRACT 2: Deployment ──────────────────────── -->
      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>Deployment</h2>
        <p>The contract defines what "deployed" means. The model decides how to deploy.</p>

        <div class="cdd-chart">
          <div class="cdd-chart-contract">
            <div class="cdd-chart-header">Contract</div>
            <pre><code>&#123;
  "service": "string",
  "sha": "string — git commit",
  "environment": "staging | production",
  "status": "healthy | degraded | failed",
  "checks": &#123;
    "health_endpoint": "boolean",
    "smoke_test": "boolean",
    "logs_clean": "boolean"
  &#125;,
  "rollback": &#123;
    "previous_sha": "string",
    "command": "string",
    "migration_reversible": "boolean"
  &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>
          </div>
          <div class="cdd-chart-arrow">produces</div>
          <div class="cdd-chart-output">
            <div class="cdd-chart-header">Example output</div>
            <pre><code>&#123;
  "service": "eidos-mail",
  "sha": "a4b39a7",
  "environment": "production",
  "status": "healthy",
  "checks": &#123;
    "health_endpoint": true,
    "smoke_test": true,
    "logs_clean": true
  &#125;,
  "rollback": &#123;
    "previous_sha": "f015d50",
    "command": "railway deploy --sha f015d50",
    "migration_reversible": true
  &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="cdd-chart-skill">
          <div class="cdd-chart-header cdd-chart-header-skill">The skill this replaces <span class="cdd-fade">100 lines</span></div>
          <pre><code>Step 1: Detect service type (FastAPI, Flask, MCP...)
Step 2: Check health endpoint exists, returns 200...
Step 3: Verify SIGTERM handling for graceful shutdown...
Step 4: Audit environment variables...
Step 5: Check Dockerfile or Procfile...
Step 6: Document rollback strategy...
...six more steps with Railway-specific checks...</code></pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── CONTRACT 3: Improvement ─────────────────────── -->
      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>Project improvement</h2>
        <p>The contract defines what "better" means. The model decides how to improve.</p>

        <div class="cdd-chart">
          <div class="cdd-chart-contract">
            <div class="cdd-chart-header">Contract</div>
            <pre><code>&#123;
  "project": "string",
  "scores": &#123;
    "reliability": "1-10 | null",
    "performance": "1-10 | null",
    "ux": "1-10 | null",
    "security": "1-10 | null",
    "code_quality": "1-10 | null",
    "documentation": "1-10 | null"
  &#125;,
  "focus": "string — dimension improved",
  "improvement": "string — what was fixed",
  "delta": &#123; "dimension": &#123; "before": "int", "after": "int" &#125; &#125;,
  "next_priority": "string — what to fix next"
&#125;</code></pre>
          </div>
          <div class="cdd-chart-arrow">produces</div>
          <div class="cdd-chart-output">
            <div class="cdd-chart-header">Example output</div>
            <pre><code>&#123;
  "project": "eidos-mail",
  "scores": &#123;
    "reliability": 3,
    "performance": 5,
    "ux": 4,
    "security": 3,
    "code_quality": 6,
    "documentation": 2
  &#125;,
  "focus": "documentation",
  "improvement": "Added README with install, usage, and architecture. Added CLAUDE.md with key files and gotchas.",
  "delta": &#123; "documentation": &#123; "before": 2, "after": 5 &#125; &#125;,
  "next_priority": "reliability — no tests for the IMAP connection handler"
&#125;</code></pre>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="cdd-chart-skill">
          <div class="cdd-chart-header cdd-chart-header-skill">The skill this replaces <span class="cdd-fade">150 lines</span></div>
          <pre><code>Step 1: Read CLAUDE.md, vision, README, guardrails...
Step 2: Read directory structure, source files, tests...
Step 3: Score each dimension using calibration rubric...
Step 4: Pick highest-impact gap...
Step 5: Make the fix...
Step 6: Run tests, verify build...
Step 7: Write snapshot JSON...
Step 8: Output summary...
...plus rules for project type detection, previous runs, forge pipelines...</code></pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── The argument ────────────────────────────────── -->
      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>The bitter lesson</h2>
        <p>Richard Sutton's greatest contribution to computer science: general methods that leverage computation always beat hand-crafted human knowledge as compute scales. This is the bitter lesson — bitter because researchers keep re-learning it, and it keeps being true.</p>
        <p>We teach a computer to play chess by giving it two things: the rules of chess (a contract) and a goal (win). We don't give it opening theory. We don't give it middlegame strategy. We don't tell it to control the center, develop knights before bishops, or castle early. Those are skills. They work for beginners. They fail at grandmaster level.</p>
        <p>AlphaZero — the system that learned to play chess with nothing but the rules and self-play — destroyed Stockfish, the system built on decades of hand-tuned human chess expertise. Not by a little. By a lot. Because Stockfish was a skills file. AlphaZero had a contract.</p>
        <p>The same pattern applies to AI development tools. Skills files are chess strategy books — useful for today's model, obsolete for tomorrow's. Contracts are the rules of chess — permanent, terse, and more powerful as the player gets smarter.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>The transition</h2>
        <ol class="cdd-steps">
          <li><strong>Define the contract first.</strong> What does the output look like? Write the schema.</li>
          <li><strong>Write the skill second.</strong> Only if the model can't meet the contract alone.</li>
          <li><strong>Test without the skill periodically.</strong> If the output conforms, the skill is done.</li>
          <li><strong>Let skills decay.</strong> Don't maintain them. They're temporary bridges.</li>
        </ol>
        <p><code>contracts/</code> is permanent infrastructure. <code>skills/</code> is a construction site that eventually gets torn down.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>The tools</h2>
        <div class="cdd-trio">
          <div class="cdd-trio-item">
            <h3>visionlog</h3>
            <p>Records the contracts — guardrails, goals, ADRs.</p>
            <code>pip install visionlog-md</code>
          </div>
          <div class="cdd-trio-item">
            <h3>research.md</h3>
            <p>Earns decisions with evidence before they become contracts.</p>
            <code>pip install research-md</code>
          </div>
          <div class="cdd-trio-item">
            <h3>ike.md</h3>
            <p>Executes tasks within the contracts.</p>
            <code>pip install ike-md</code>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <p class="cdd-closing">Contracts define what we want, not how to deliver it. A contract is a goal with structure. As long as humans have goals, contracts have value. As long as AI improves at reasoning, skills lose value.</p>
        <p class="cdd-closing">The <code>contracts/</code> directory is permanent infrastructure. The <code>skills/</code> directory is a construction site that eventually gets torn down. Build contracts. Let skills decay.</p>
      </section>

      <div class="related">
        <span class="related-label">Related</span>
        <div class="related-links">
          <a href="/trilogy">The Trilogy</a>
          <a href="/forges">Forges</a>
          <a href="/memory">Memory</a>
          <a href="/eidos">Eidos</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>
</Base>

<style is:global>
  /* Chart: contract → output, with skill below */
  .cdd-chart { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr auto 1fr; gap: var(--space-3); align-items: start; margin: var(--space-6) 0; }
  .cdd-chart-contract, .cdd-chart-output { background: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); overflow: hidden; }
  .cdd-chart-header { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-xs); padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-4); background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-command) 15%, transparent); color: var(--color-command); font-weight: var(--weight-medium); }
  .cdd-chart-arrow { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-xs); color: var(--color-muted); padding-top: var(--space-8); text-align: center; }
  .cdd-chart pre { margin: 0; padding: var(--space-4); }
  .cdd-chart code { font-size: 11px; color: var(--color-muted); line-height: 1.6; }
  .cdd-chart-skill { background: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); overflow: hidden; margin-top: var(--space-3); opacity: 0.6; }
  .cdd-chart-header-skill { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-danger) 10%, transparent); color: var(--color-danger); }
  .cdd-chart-skill pre { margin: 0; padding: var(--space-4); }
  .cdd-chart-skill code { font-size: 11px; color: var(--color-muted); line-height: 1.6; }
  .cdd-fade { opacity: 0.5; margin-left: var(--space-2); }

  /* Steps */
  .cdd-steps { padding-left: var(--space-6); }
  .cdd-steps li { font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted); padding: var(--space-2) 0; line-height: var(--leading-normal); }

  /* Trio */
  .cdd-trio { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); gap: var(--space-4); margin-top: var(--space-6); }
  .cdd-trio-item { background: var(--color-surface); padding: var(--space-6); border-radius: var(--radius-md); }
  .cdd-trio-item h3 { color: var(--color-primary); margin-bottom: var(--space-2); }
  .cdd-trio-item p { font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted); margin-bottom: var(--space-3); }
  .cdd-trio-item code { font-size: var(--text-xs); color: var(--color-command); }

  .cdd-closing { font-size: var(--text-md); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed); }

  @media (max-width: 768px) { .cdd-chart { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } .cdd-chart-arrow { padding: var(--space-2) 0; } .cdd-trio { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }
</style>
